│ to decide whether it needs to multiply the vector step by the scalar step. The check uses getZExtValue() == 1.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe code assumes the │
│ step fits within 64 bits when examining whether the step equals 1. This is not valid for wider integer types (like i65) or when the step is negative. Using     │
│ getZExtValue() both imposes a 64-bit limit and is semantically wrong for signed negative values. LLVM provides ConstantInt::isOne(), which safely checks        │
│ whether the constant equals 1 regardless of bitwidth or sign. Thus, the crash is caused by the incorrect use of getZExtValue() to test for the value 1 on       │
